<taxonomicName authorityName="Nasarow" authorityYear="1936" box="[406,529,1874,1900]" class="Ascidiacea" family="Polycitoridae" genus="Salix" kingdom="Animalia" order="Enterogona" pageId="4" pageNumber="385" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="turanica">
<emphasis box="[406,529,1874,1900]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="385">S. turanica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<date box="[542,686,1873,1900]" pageId="4" pageNumber="385" value="2019-06-24">
<collectingDate box="[542,686,1873,1900]" pageId="4" pageNumber="385" value="2019-06-24">24. VI. 2019</collectingDate>
</date>
, signals of 
<specimenCount box="[813,888,1873,1899]" pageId="4" pageNumber="385" type="male">1 male</specimenCount>
recorded at 25 
<superScript attach="right" box="[1062,1092,1873,1899]" fontSize="6" pageId="4" pageNumber="385">oC</superScript>
</materialsCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,1945,2008]" lastBlockId="5.[151,1437,151,933]" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="386" pageId="4" pageNumber="385">
Calling signal is a single or repeated phrase lasting from 10–15 up to 30–40 s and consisting of two parts differing from each other in temporal pattern and frequency spectra (
<figureCitation box="[913,1054,1981,2008]" captionStart="FIGURES 82–91" captionStartId="16.[151,264,1956,1980]" captionTargetBox="[180,1405,188,1918]" captionTargetId="figure-25@16.[167,1420,181,1932]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 82–91. Male calling signals of M. iliensis from different regions. 82, 84–91―oscillograms, 83―sonogram of signal presented on Fig. 84. Faster oscillograms of the parts of signals indicated as “86–91” are given under the same numbers." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4404169" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4404169/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="385">Figs. 82–85</figureCitation>
). The first part is a succession of syllables variable in length and following against the background of a continuous low-amplitude vibrations; pulse repetition rate in syllables averages 70–90/s (
<figureCitation box="[672,813,187,214]" captionStart="FIGURES 82–91" captionStartId="16.[151,264,1956,1980]" captionTargetBox="[180,1405,188,1918]" captionTargetId="figure-25@16.[167,1420,181,1932]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 82–91. Male calling signals of M. iliensis from different regions. 82, 84–91―oscillograms, 83―sonogram of signal presented on Fig. 84. Faster oscillograms of the parts of signals indicated as “86–91” are given under the same numbers." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4404169" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4404169/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="386">Figs. 86–88</figureCitation>
). The second part includes 2–6 discrete syllables each ending with abrupt amplitude outbreak and consisting of short uniform pulses; pulse repetition rate in syllables of the second part is much higher and averages 150–200/s (
<figureCitation box="[785,923,259,285]" captionStart="FIGURES 82–91" captionStartId="16.[151,264,1956,1980]" captionTargetBox="[180,1405,188,1918]" captionTargetId="figure-25@16.[167,1420,181,1932]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 82–91. Male calling signals of M. iliensis from different regions. 82, 84–91―oscillograms, 83―sonogram of signal presented on Fig. 84. Faster oscillograms of the parts of signals indicated as “86–91” are given under the same numbers." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4404169" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4404169/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="386">Figs. 89–91</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="386" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,151,933]" pageId="5" pageNumber="386">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,262,295,321]" pageId="5" pageNumber="386">Host.</emphasis>
In 
<collectingCountry box="[304,435,295,321]" name="Kazakhstan" pageId="5" pageNumber="386">Kazakhstan</collectingCountry>
and Central Asia was found on 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Nasarow" authorityYear="1936" box="[810,970,295,321]" class="Ascidiacea" family="Polycitoridae" genus="Salix" kingdom="Animalia" order="Enterogona" pageId="5" pageNumber="386" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="turanica">
<emphasis box="[810,970,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="386">Salix turanica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(section 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1870" box="[1077,1184,295,321]" class="Anthozoa" family="Ellisellidae" genus="Viminella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="5" pageNumber="386" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1077,1184,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="386">Viminella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); in 
<collectingCountry box="[1242,1317,295,321]" name="Russia" pageId="5" pageNumber="386">Russia</collectingCountry>
(Southern Urals) one series of specimens was collected on 
<taxonomicName authorityName="A.K.Skvortsov" authorityYear="1966" box="[694,865,331,357]" class="Ascidiacea" family="Polycitoridae" genus="Salix" kingdom="Animalia" order="Enterogona" pageId="5" pageNumber="386" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="vinogradovii">
<emphasis box="[694,865,331,357]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="386">S. vinogradovii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(section 
<taxonomicName box="[968,1029,331,357]" class="Gastropoda" family="Helicidae" genus="Helix" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="5" pageNumber="386" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[968,1029,331,357]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="386">Helix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="386" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,151,933]" pageId="5" pageNumber="386">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,366,392]" pageId="5" pageNumber="386">Distribution.</emphasis>
The whole territory of 
<collectingCountry box="[625,759,367,393]" name="Kazakhstan" pageId="5" pageNumber="386">Kazakhstan</collectingCountry>
, mountains of Central Asia (North and Central Tien Shan); reaches Southern Urals, 
<collectingCountry box="[433,508,403,429]" name="Russia" pageId="5" pageNumber="386">Russia</collectingCountry>
in the extreme northwest of the range and Southern Siberia (
<collectingRegion box="[1219,1278,403,429]" country="Russia" name="Tyva" pageId="5" pageNumber="386">Tyva</collectingRegion>
) and Western Mongolia in the extreme northeast. In 
<collectingCountry box="[589,720,439,465]" name="Kazakhstan" pageId="5" pageNumber="386">Kazakhstan</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[776,905,439,465]" name="Kyrgyzstan" pageId="5" pageNumber="386">Kyrgyzstan</collectingCountry>
was found on almost all investigated plants of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Nasarow" authorityYear="1936" box="[151,274,475,501]" class="Ascidiacea" family="Polycitoridae" genus="Salix" kingdom="Animalia" order="Enterogona" pageId="5" pageNumber="386" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="turanica">
<emphasis box="[151,274,475,501]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="386">S. turanica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
